\subsection{Synthesis}

Across all tests:
\[
\lambda < 1 \Rightarrow \text{Convergent},\quad
\lambda = 1 \Rightarrow \text{Marginal},\quad
\lambda > 1 \Rightarrow \text{Expansive}.
\]
This partition is universal across system types, dimensionality, and substrate.

% =====================================================================
% DROP 8 — BIOLOGICAL VALIDATION (EEG) + DISCUSSION + CONCLUSION
% =====================================================================

\section{Biological Validation (EEG)}
\label{sec:eeg}

Neural dynamics provide a critical test: if CRIS describes persistent systems generally, then stable brain states must exhibit the predicted structure. We analyze human sleep EEG using the same measurement protocol validated on synthetic and physical systems, with explicit tests for exponentiality, parameter invariance, and substrate independence. No training data or state labels are used in $\eta$ estimation. The resulting contraction hierarchy (N3 deeply convergent, REM marginal, wake near-critical) emerges from geometric structure rather than statistical correlation, suggesting that brain state organization reflects fundamental stability constraints rather than domain-specific mechanisms.

This section establishes biological validity of the contraction--projection
framework using publicly available, de-identified EEG.
All computations follow
the falsification protocols of Section~\ref{sec:empirical} and Section~\ref{sec:falsification}, with
explicit tests for exponentiality, invariance, and substrate independence.

\subsection{Datasets and preprocessing}
\label{subsec:eeg_data}

We used cohort-scale sleep EEG from public repositories, including the Sleep-EDF Expanded dataset \cite{Kemp2000,Goldberger2000}, with polysomnographic staging into Wake, REM, and N3 (deep sleep).
No new human data
were collected. Preprocessing adhered to a fixed, audit-ready pipeline:

\begin{enumerate}[label=\textbf{P.\arabic*}]
\item \textbf{Filtering.} Linear-phase FIR bandpass $0.5$--$45$ Hz;
notch at local line
frequency (quality factor $\ge 30$).
\item \textbf{Artifact rejection.} Channel outliers flagged by median absolute deviation
in high-frequency power and line-noise indices;
bad channels reconstructed by spherical
spline interpolation; epochs exceeding amplitude or kurtosis thresholds discarded.
\item \textbf{Referencing.} Common average reference after channel repair.
\item \textbf{Windowing.} Non-overlapping or $50\%$-overlapped $30$ s windows;
windows
with $<90\%$ valid samples excluded.
\end{enumerate}

All pipeline parameters and SHA256 digests are enumerated in the Reproducibility
Appendix (see the \nameref{sec:reproducibility-main} section).

\subsection{Signal representation: analytic-coherence envelope}
\label{subsec:eeg_representation}

Let $x_c(t)$ denote the cleaned time series from channel $c$ within a valid
window.
Define the analytic signal via the Hilbert transform $h_c(t)=\mathrm{hilbert}(x_c(t))$ and envelope $e_c(t)=|h_c(t)|$, following standard analytic-coherence envelope construction \cite{Lachaux1999,Cohen2014}.
Construct the
feature vector $z_n$ for window $n$ by either channel-averaging
$z_n = \frac{1}{C}\sum_c \langle e_c \rangle_{\text{window}}$ or channel-stacking
$z_n \in \mathbb{R}^{C}$ with entries $\langle e_c \rangle_{\text{window}}$.
Both are admissible under invariance tests below. This yields a time series $\{z_n\}_{n\ge 0}$ in a Hilbert geometry where the Euclidean metric is the operative norm (cf.\ \cite{Gramfort2014}).

\subsection{Recursion operator and observable}
\label{subsec:eeg_recursion}

Define a strictly contractive linear smoother $E$ with $\ell_2$-gain $<1$
(e.g., Tukey-tapered moving average of order $m\in\{3,5,7\}$).
Fix $\alpha\in(0,1]$
and set the averaged recursion operator
\[
F_\alpha \;=\; (1-\alpha)\Id + \alpha E.
\]
The observable persistence functional is
\[
P_n \;:=\; \|z_n - z_{n+1}\|_2,\qquad
\log P_n \approx a - \gamma_\alpha n,
\]
with measured contraction factor $\lambda_\alpha = e^{-\gamma_\alpha}$.
By Proposition~\ref{prop:eta-recovery}, the intrinsic contraction
$\eta$ is recovered from the runtime constant via \eqref{eq:eta_recovery}.

\subsection{Estimator correctness and invariance: proofs}
\label{subsec:eeg_correctness}

\begin{lemma}[Fixed-point invariance under averaging]
\label{lem:eeg_fix_invariance}
$\mathrm{Fix}(F_\alpha)=\mathrm{Fix}(F)$ for every $\alpha\in(0,1]$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
Identical to Proposition~\ref{prop:fix-invariance}: $F_\alpha(x)=x$ iff
$F(x)=x$ because $F_\alpha=(1-\alpha)\Id+\alpha F$ and $\alpha>0$.
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}[Contraction constant of $F_\alpha$]
\label{lem:eeg_qalpha}
If $F$ is $\eta$-Lipschitz with $\eta\in(0,1)$, then
$q_\alpha=1-\alpha(1-\eta)$ is the Lipschitz constant of $F_\alpha$, with
$\eta \le q_\alpha < 1$ for $\alpha\in(0,1)$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
As in Theorem~\ref{thm:qalpha},
$\|F_\alpha x - F_\alpha y\|\le (1-\alpha)\|x-y\| + \alpha\eta\|x-y\|$.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Intrinsic recovery from runtime measurement]
\label{prop:eeg_eta_recovery}
Let $\lambda_\alpha$ be the measured contraction factor of $F_\alpha$.
If
$\alpha\in(0,1]$ is known and $F$ is $\eta$-Lipschitz, then $\eta$ is recovered
exactly by \eqref{eq:eta_recovery}.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
From Lemma~\ref{lem:eeg_qalpha}, $\lambda_\alpha=q_\alpha=1-\alpha(1-\eta)$. Solve
for $\eta$ to obtain \eqref{eq:eta_recovery}. For $\alpha=1$, $\eta=\lambda_1$.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Estimator consistency under the persistence model]
\label{prop:persistence_consistency}
Assume the persistence functional follows the model
$\log P_n = a - \gamma_\alpha n + \varepsilon_n$ with $\varepsilon_n$ zero-mean,
weakly dependent, and finite variance, and that $F_\alpha$ is time-homogeneous.
Then the OLS slope $\widehat{\gamma}_\alpha$ is a consistent estimator of
$\gamma_\alpha=-\ln \lambda_\alpha$, and $\widehat{\eta}$ recovered via
\eqref{eq:eta_recovery} is a consistent estimator of $\eta$.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
Standard linear regression consistency (LLN and ergodic theorem) implies
$\widehat{\gamma}_\alpha \xrightarrow{p} \gamma_\alpha$.
The mapping
$\widehat{\eta}=((e^{-\widehat{\gamma}_\alpha})-(1-\alpha)) / \alpha$ is continuous
near $\gamma_\alpha$, so the continuous mapping theorem yields
$\widehat{\eta}\xrightarrow{p}\eta$.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Engine/parameter invariance]
\label{prop:eeg_invariance}
Let $m$ denote the smoothing order of $E$ and $\alpha\in(0,1]$. If $E$ remains
strictly contractive and the underlying dynamics are stationary on the windowed
timescale, then $\widehat{\eta}$ is invariant (to tolerance) under changes in
$(m,\alpha)$, while $\widehat{\lambda}_\alpha$ changes according to
$q_\alpha=1-\alpha(1-\eta)$.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
By Lemma~\ref{lem:eeg_qalpha} and Proposition~\ref{prop:eeg_eta_recovery}, varying
$\alpha$ alters the runtime constant but the recovered $\eta$ is fixed. If changing
$m$ preserves contractivity and time-homogeneity, the same argument holds.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Substrate invariance]
\label{prop:eeg_substrate}
Let $\mathcal{E}$ be any lossless re-encoding of $\{z_n\}$ (e.g., float32, int64,
string). Then $\widehat{\eta}$ computed from $\mathcal{E}(\{z_n\})$ equals
$\widehat{\eta}$ from $\{z_n\}$ up to numerical precision.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
Lossless re-encoding preserves Euclidean distances underlying $P_n$;
therefore
$\lambda_\alpha$ is unchanged up to machine precision, and so is $\eta$ by
\eqref{eq:eta_recovery}.
\end{proof}

\subsection{EEG results: contraction hierarchy and transitions}
\label{subsec:eeg_results}

