\FloatBarrier

\subsection{Clinical and theoretical implications}
\label{subsec:eeg_implications}

\begin{enumerate}[label=\textbf{C.\arabic*}]
\item \textbf{Order parameter for state.} $\eta$ functions as a substrate-independent
order parameter: N3 occupies a deeply convergent basin;
REM lies on the marginal
manifold ($\eta\approx 1$); wake remains near-critical but convergent.
\item \textbf{Anesthetic depth.} Induction corresponds to a drift from near-critical
($\eta\approx 0.99$) toward strong convergence ($\eta < 0.95$); emergence reverses
this trajectory.
Real-time $\hat{\eta}$ enables closed-loop titration.
\item \textbf{Seizure warning.} Pre-ictal dynamics should exhibit excursions with
$\eta>1$ (expansive).
A thresholded detector on $\hat{\eta}$ with Protocol
\ref{prot:ratio} can act as an early-warning system.
\item \textbf{Disorders of consciousness.} Coma/deep anesthesia map to extended
residence in strongly convergent basins (very low $\eta$);
vegetative or minimally
conscious states may reflect impaired access to the REM manifold (loss of marginal
plateaus), testable via $\eta$-based staging.
\item \textbf{Mechanistic unification.} The same contraction spectrum explains
sleep cycling, anesthetic modulation, and seizure instability within a single
geometric classifier, independent of sensor idiosyncrasies.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Falsification gates (biological)}
\label{subsec:eeg_falsification}

The EEG results validate the framework only under the admissibility conditions.
Violations that falsify the model for a given dataset include:

\begin{itemize}
\item Failure of exponential decay (Protocol~\ref{prot:persistence} rejection).
\item Instability of the contraction ratio (Protocol~\ref{prot:ratio} rejection).
\item Dependence of recovered $\eta$ on $(m,\alpha)$ beyond tolerance
($10^{-2}$), contradicting Proposition~\ref{prop:eeg_invariance}.
\item Substrate dependence beyond numerical precision,
contradicting Proposition~\ref{prop:eeg_substrate}.
\end{itemize}

Such failures exclude the dataset or condition from the admissible class without
challenging the mathematical theorems.

\subsection{Relation to Established Stability Theory}
\label{sec:relation_established}

The CRIS framework recovers known results as special cases:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.2em]
\item \textbf{Banach fixed-point theorem:} Direct application of Theorem~\ref{thm:main} with $\mathcal{C}=\mathcal{H}$.
\item \textbf{Thermodynamic equilibrium:} Marginal contraction ($\eta \to 1$) corresponds to reversible processes; $\eta<1$ characterizes dissipation toward equilibrium.
\item \textbf{Lyapunov stability:} The constructed $V$ in Lemma~\ref{lem:lyap} is a Lyapunov function; CRIS shows this construction is always possible for globally stable systems.
\item \textbf{Information channels:} Contraction in Hellinger geometry (Section~\ref{sec:stochastic}) yields convergence to the stationary distribution; for BSC, $\eta=|1-2\epsilon|$ exactly (Theorem~\ref{thm:bsc_exact}).
\item \textbf{Quantum decoherence:} Depolarizing channel contraction in Hilbert–Schmidt geometry (Lemma~\ref{lem:hs_depol}) quantifies approach to the maximally mixed state.
\end{itemize}
These connections are not analogies but identities: each stability criterion is a statement about the $\eta$–structure in the appropriate geometry.


% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Universality in form, scope in domain.}
The forward direction (Theorem~\ref{thm:main}) proves that any $F=P_{\mathcal{C}}\circ E$ with
$\eta<1$ has a unique fixed point, exponential convergence, and coercivity.
The necessity direction (Section~\ref{sec:necessity}) shows that any system with a unique globally
attracting fixed point and spectral stability admits a canonical factorization
$F=R\circ E$ in an appropriate Hilbert geometry (after isometric embedding).
Therefore the representation is \emph{universal in form}. The empirical gates of
Section~\ref{sec:falsification} ensure the scope is appropriately constrained: the law does not assert
convergence for conservative or supercritical systems;
it classifies them
($\lambda=1$ marginal; $\lambda>1$ expansive).

\paragraph{Scope and interpretation.}
We do not claim that CRIS encompasses all of physics or reduces all phenomena to operator theory. The claim is conditional: if a system maintains stable identity through recursive transformation, then it must have the CRIS structure. Many important phenomena (symmetry breaking, phase transitions, non-equilibrium transients) lie outside the CRIS domain. However, equilibrium states, attractors, steady states, and fixed points across diverse domains do satisfy A1–A4, and thus admit the canonical representation. The $\eta$ classifier does not replace domain-specific theories; it identifies their common geometric skeleton.

\paragraph{Separation of physics and instrumentation.}
Theorem~\ref{thm:qalpha} established $q_\alpha=1-\alpha(1-\eta)$ and exact recovery of $\eta$,
preventing confounds from numerical stabilization.
Section~\ref{sec:substrate_invariance_results} (Substrate Invariance)
demonstrated machine-precision invariance across encodings. Section~\ref{sec:eeg} extended these
invariances to physiological data.
Hence the measured $\eta$ is a property of
realized dynamics, not a byproduct of preprocessing.

\paragraph{Universality classes via $(\eta,\mathcal{C})$.}
Systems with identical intrinsic $\eta$ and congruent constraint geometry
$(\mathcal{C})$ fall into the same universality class under the categorical
framework of Section~\ref{sec:categorical}.
This yields a parsimonious cataloging of dynamics that
cuts across stochastic, quantum, classical, and biological substrates.

\paragraph{Limits and extensions.}
Hilbert geometry and convex recovery are essential here; nonconvex recoveries and
Banach generalizations require monotone operator or Bregman extensions.
Near the
critical manifold ($\eta\to 1$), finite-sample effects lengthen transients; the
model selection guardrails in Section~\ref{sec:falsification} are required for robust inference.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We have proven that persistent recursive systems (those satisfying consistency, recursion, invariance, and selection) must admit a unique canonical factorization $F = R \circ E$ in Hilbert geometry. This necessity result establishes CRIS not as a model but as a structural constraint on stable dynamics.
We separated intrinsic contraction $\eta$ from
runtime parameters, provided falsification gates, and validated the classifier
across synthetic, physical, stochastic, quantum, and biological domains.
EEG
results show that deep sleep, REM, and wakefulness occupy distinct positions on
the contraction spectrum, supporting a geometric account of neural state
organization.
The law is universal in representation and testable in scope.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section*{Reproducibility and audit ledger}
\label{sec:reproducibility-main}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Code and parameters.} Reference implementation: commit hash and
parameter ledger (filters, $m\in\{3,5,7\}$; $\alpha\in\{0.3,0.5,0.7,0.9,1.0\}$).
\item \textbf{Data provenance.} Dataset names, subject IDs (de-identified), and
file SHA256 digests; staging label distributions per subject; window counts.
\item \textbf{Falsification reports.} For each cohort: AIC model selection logs
(M1 vs.\ M2), residual diagnostics, contraction ratio traces with burn-in $n_{\mathrm{burn}}$,
and invariance sweeps over $(m,\alpha)$.
\item \textbf{Numerical precision.} Substrate round-trip tests documenting equality within
double-precision limits ($\approx 10^{-16}$) for $\lambda_\alpha$ and recovered $\eta$.
\end{itemize}

